If I write a lambda in a tuple and type a semicolon after the tuple or ask Visual Studio to fix indentation for the file, it adds a newline between the lambda‚Äôs closing curly brace and the tuple‚Äôs closing parenthesis. This seems odd. I would expect a newline between the opening parenthesis and first value in the tuple if this were considered the desired style. However, I don‚Äôt think it is the desired style for tuples.

I generally expect the styling of tuple parens to be the same as function argument list parens.

Before typing the semicolon:
```csharp
var plan = new List<(int count, Action<int> action)>();
plan.Add((2, i =>
{
    Console.WriteLine($"Action (execution {i})");
}))
```


After typing the semicolon after the tuple.:
```csharp
var plan = new List<(int count, Action<int> action)>();
plan.Add((2, i =>
{
    Console.WriteLine($"Action (execution {i})");
}
));
```

Expected:
```csharp
var plan = new List<(int count, Action<int> action)>();
plan.Add((2, i =>
{
    Console.WriteLine($"Action (execution {i})");
}));
```

